Pour the @water{300%ml} for the rice into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil. When boiling, stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and 0.25 tsp of @salt{0.25%tsp}, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, trim the @green beans{150%g} then chop into thirds. Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Zest and quarter the @lime{1}. Peel and grate the @ginger{1%thumb-sized piece}. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(stalks and leaves separated).

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the @British beef mince{240%g} and @Chinese five spice{1/2%tsp} and stir-fry until browned, ~{6-8%minutes}, breaking it up with a #wooden spoon{} as it cooks. When the beef is cooked, drain off any excess fat and transfer to a #small bowl{} and set to one side. Keep the pan!

Return the now empty frying pan to medium-high heat (add another splash of oil if dry!). Once hot, add the pepper, green beans and a small splash of water to help them cook. Stir-fry for ~{4-5%minutes} until tender. Stir in the ginger and garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute} then stir in the @soy sauce{25%ml}, @ketjap manis{25%ml} and @sugar{1%tsp}.

Add the beef mince back into the pan and stir in the cooked rice. Toss to combine and continue to cook until piping hot, ~{2-3%minutes}. Once hot, remove the pan from the heat and stir in the lime zest, juice from half the lime and half the coriander.

Divide the fried rice between your #bowls{} and sprinkle over the remaining coriander. Serve with the remaining wedges of lime on the side to squeeze on top. Enjoy!